<section xml:id="C11.S6">
<title>Asymptotic Expansions</title>        
 
<subsection xml:id="C11.S6.SS1">
<title>Large <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.m1">|z|</Math>, Fixed <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.m2">\nu</Math></title>          
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="11.6.1" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E1">\mathbf{K}_{\nu}\left(z\right)\sim\frac{1}{\pi}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Gamma \left(k+\tfrac{1}{2}\right)(\tfrac{1}{2}z)^{\nu-2k-1}}{\Gamma\left(\nu+\tfrac{ 1}{2}-k\right)}, if |\operatorname{ph}z|\leq\pi-\delta,</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m1">\delta</Math> is an arbitrary small positive constant.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.s2">
If the series on the right-hand side of (11.6.1) is truncated after <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m2">m(\geq 0)</Math> terms, then the remainder term <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m3">R_{m}(z)</Math> is <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m4">O\left(z^{\nu-2m-1}\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.s3">
If <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m5">\nu</Math> is real, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m6">z</Math> is positive, and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m7">m+\tfrac{1}{2}-\nu\geq 0</Math> , then <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p1.m8">R_{m}(z)</Math> is of the same sign and numerically less than the first neglected term.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p2.s1">
 <Math equation-number="11.6.2" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E2">\mathbf{M}_{\nu}\left(z\right)\sim\frac{1}{\pi}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}(-1)^{k+1} \frac{\Gamma\left(k+\tfrac{1}{2}\right)(\tfrac{1}{2}z)^{\nu-2k-1}}{\Gamma\left (\nu+\tfrac{1}{2}-k\right)}, if |\operatorname{ph}z|\leq\tfrac{1}{2}\pi-\delta</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p3.s1">
For re-expansions of the remainder terms in (11.6.1) and (11.6.2),see Dingle (1973, p. 445).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p4">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p4.s1">
For the corresponding expansions for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p4.m1">\mathbf{H}_{\nu}\left(z\right)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p4.m2">\mathbf{L}_{\nu}\left(z\right)</Math> combine (11.6.1),(11.6.2) with (11.2.5), (11.2.6), (10.17.4), and (10.40.1).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p4.s2">
<Math equation-number="11.6.3" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E3">\int_{0}^{z}\mathbf{K}_{0}\left(t\right)\mathrm{d}t-\frac{2}{\pi}(\ln\left(2z \right)+\gamma)\sim\frac{2}{\pi}\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}(-1)^{k+1}\frac{(2k)!(2k-1) !}{(k!)^{2}(2z)^{2k}}, if |\operatorname{ph}z|\leq\pi-\delta,</Math> <Math equation-number="11.6.4" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E4">\int_{0}^{z}\mathbf{M}_{0}\left(t\right)\mathrm{d}t+\frac{2}{\pi}(\ln\left(2z \right)+\gamma)\sim\frac{2}{\pi}\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{(2k)!(2k-1)!}{(k!)^{2 }(2z)^{2k}}, if |\operatorname{ph}z|\leq\tfrac{1}{2}\pi-\delta,</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS1.p4.m3">\gamma</Math> is Euler’s constant (§5.2(ii)).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C11.S6.SS2">
<title>Large <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS2.m1">|\nu|</Math>, Fixed <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS2.m2">z</Math></title>          
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C11.S6.SS2.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="11.6.5" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E5">\mathbf{H}_{\nu}\left(z\right),\mathbf{L}_{\nu}\left(z\right)\sim\frac{z}{\pi \nu\sqrt{2}}\left(\frac{ez}{2\nu}\right)^{\nu}, if |\operatorname{ph}\nu|\leq\pi-\delta</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS2.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C11.S6.SS2.p2.s1">
More fully, the series (11.2.1) and (11.2.2) can be regarded as generalized asymptotic expansions (§2.1(v)).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C11.S6.SS3">
<title>Large <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.m1">|\nu|</Math>, Fixed <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.m2">z/\nu</Math></title>        
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p1.s1">
For fixed <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p1.m1">\lambda(&gt;1)</Math> <Math equation-number="11.6.6" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E6">\mathbf{K}_{\nu}\left(\lambda\nu\right)\sim\frac{(\tfrac{1}{2}\lambda\nu)^{\nu -1}}{\sqrt{\pi}\Gamma\left(\nu+\tfrac{1}{2}\right)}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{k! c_{k}(\lambda)}{\nu^{k}}, if |\operatorname{ph}\nu|\leq\tfrac{1}{2}\pi-\delta,</Math> and for fixed <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p1.m2">\lambda</Math> <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p1.m3">(&gt;0)</Math> 
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p2.s1">
 <Math equation-number="11.6.7" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E7">\mathbf{M}_{\nu}\left(\lambda\nu\right)\sim-\frac{(\frac{1}{2}\lambda\nu)^{\nu -1}}{\sqrt{\pi}\Gamma\left(\nu+\frac{1}{2}\right)}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{k!c _{k}(i\lambda)}{\nu^{k}}, if |\operatorname{ph}\nu|\leq\frac{1}{2}\pi-\delta</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p2.s2">
Here <Math equation-number="11.6.8" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E8">c_{0}(\lambda)=1,c_{1}(\lambda)=2\lambda^{-2},c_{2}(\lambda)=6\lambda^{-4}-\tfrac{1}{2}\lambda^{-2},c_{3}(\lambda)=20\lambda^{-6}-4\lambda^{-4},c_{4}(\lambda)=70\lambda^{-8}-\tfrac{45}{2}\lambda^{-6}+\tfrac{3}{8}\lambda^{- 4}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p2.s3">
These and higher coefficients <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p2.m1">c_{k}(\lambda)</Math> can be computed via the representations in Nemes (2015b).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p3.s1">
For the corresponding result for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p3.m1">\mathbf{H}_{\nu}\left(\lambda\nu\right)</Math> use (11.2.5) and (10.19.6).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="15" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p3.s2">
See alsoWatson (1944, p. 336).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p4">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="16" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p4.s1">
For fixed <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p4.m1">\lambda</Math> <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C11.S6.SS3.p4.m2">(&gt;0)</Math> <Math equation-number="11.6.9" mode="display" xml:id="C11.S6.E9">\mathbf{L}_{\nu}\left(\lambda\nu\right)\sim I_{\nu}\left(\lambda\nu\right), if |\operatorname{ph}\nu|\leq\tfrac{1}{2}\pi-\delta,</Math> and for an estimate of the relative error in this approximation seeWatson (1944, p. 336).
</sentence>

</para>

 
</subsection>
 
</section>
